## 9. Minimum Security Controls

### 9.1 Access Control (AC)

**AC-3 — Access Enforcement**

Access to all EC2 compute resources is enforced through IAM role-based access control. An IAM role with a scoped least-privilege policy is attached to the EC2 instance profile, granting only the permissions required for Systems Manager Session Manager connectivity. No additional IAM permissions are granted to instance roles. All access enforcement configurations are version-controlled in Terraform.

**AC-6 — Least Privilege**

The IAM policy attached to the EC2 instance role is explicitly scoped to SSM-required actions only: `ssm:StartSession`, `ssmmessages:CreateControlChannel`, `ssmmessages:CreateDataChannel`, `ssmmessages:OpenControlChannel`, `ssmmessages:OpenDataChannel`, and `ec2messages:*`. No `AdministratorAccess` or broad AWS managed policies are attached. The principle of least privilege is enforced by policy design, not by convention.

**AC-17 — Remote Access**

Remote access to EC2 instances is provided exclusively through AWS Systems Manager Session Manager. No SSH key pairs are generated, stored, or associated with any instance. No inbound port 22 rules exist in any Security Group. Session Manager provides encrypted, IAM-authenticated, and auditable remote access without exposing network attack surface.

---

### 9.2 Configuration Management (CM)

**CM-2 — Baseline Configuration**

The authoritative baseline configuration for all AWS resources is defined as Terraform Infrastructure as Code. All resource configurations — VPC, subnets, route tables, IAM roles, EC2 instances — are defined in `.tf` files and stored in version control. Changes to the environment are made exclusively through Terraform plan/apply workflows, ensuring the codebase reflects the current deployed state at all times.

**CM-8 — Information System Component Inventory**

All Terraform-provisioned resources are tagged with a consistent schema: `Environment`, `Project`, `ManagedBy`, and `NISTControl`. Tags directly map each resource to its associated NIST 800-53 control family. The tagging schema enables automated inventory queries through AWS Config and AWS Tag Editor, supporting continuous inventory accuracy without manual tracking.

---

### 9.3 System and Communications Protection (SC)

**SC-7 — Boundary Protection**

Network boundary protection is implemented through a layered VPC architecture. The Internet Gateway defines the external boundary. Separate route tables for public and private subnets enforce traffic flow — private subnet resources have no route to the Internet Gateway. Security Groups provide stateful instance-level boundary enforcement, permitting only explicitly authorized traffic. No private subnet resources are directly reachable from the internet.

**SC-28 — Protection of Information at Rest**

EBS root volumes on all EC2 instances are encrypted using AWS-managed KMS keys (aws/ebs). Encryption is enforced at the Terraform resource level via `encrypted = true` on the root block device configuration. An AWS Config managed rule (`encrypted-volumes`) will be implemented to continuously detect and alert on any unencrypted EBS volumes within the account.

